-- Gödel Fixed Point in ProbTT
--
-- NOTE: This file DEMONSTRATES the proof checker syntax.
-- The actual metatheory is formalized in agda/ProbTT/Incompleteness.agda
--
-- LITERATURE: Hájek-Paris-Shepherdson, "The Liar Paradox and Fuzzy Logic" (2000)
-- The w = 1-w → w = 1/2 result is standard in fuzzy logic self-reference.
--
-- Classical: G is undecidable (neither provable nor refutable)
-- ProbTT: G has weight 1/2 (the fixed point of negation)
--
-- G = "G has weight 0" = "G is unprovable at weight 1"
-- If G @ w, then by G's content, w should equal 0
-- But if w = 0, then ¬G @ 1, so G @ 1 (contradiction)
-- Resolution: w = ¬w, which has unique solution w = 1/2

-- Encode the Gödel sentence
encode G = Unprov_G

-- The Gödel sentence asserts its own unprovability
-- G ↔ ¬Prov_1(G)
-- If Prov(G) @ w, then G's meaning implies w should satisfy w = ¬w

-- Assume G at some weight w
postulate g : G 〔 w 〕

-- Self-reference: G claims "Prov(G) @ 0"
-- So if G @ w, then Prov(G) @ 0 should hold
derive g_claims : Prov_G_zero 〔 w 〕 from g by self_reference

-- But we assumed Prov(G) @ w, not 0
-- The only consistent resolution: w = ¬w

-- Solve the fixpoint equation: w = ¬w → w = 1/2
fixpoint godel_w = ¬godel_w

-- The Gödel sentence has determinate weight 1/2
-- This is not undecidability - it's maximal uncertainty
-- At w = 1/2, "G is somewhat true" and "G is somewhat false" both hold
-- This is the unique stable equilibrium

-- Provability of G at weight 1/2
provable godel_provability : G 〔 1/2 〕

-- Key insight: Classical logic only has {0,1}
-- The equation w = ¬w has no solution in {0,1}
-- Hence classical undecidability
-- But in [0,1], w = 1-w has the solution w = 1/2
